An integer $n$ is said to be square-free if the only perfect square that divides $n$ is $1^2$. How many positive odd integers greater than 1 and less than $100$ are square-free?

Solution: 
The odd integers greater than 1 and less than $100$ are $3, 5, 7, \cdots, 99$. The perfect squares less than $100$ are $1, 4, 9, \cdots, 81$. Therefore, the odd integers greater than 1 and less than $100$ that are not square-free are $9, 25, 49, 81$. So, the number of positive odd integers greater than 1 and less than $100$ that are square-free is $49$.
Final Answer: $\boxed{49}.$ I hope it is correct.

Six of them are odd and five are even. There are $3$ multiples of $25$ that are less than $100$. Two of them are odd and one is even. There are $2$ multiples of $49$ that are less than $100$. One of them is odd and one is even. Therefore, there are $9$ odd integers that are not square-free. Therefore, there are 9 odd integers less than 100 which are divisible by a perfect square greater than 1. There are $49$ odd integers less than $100$ and greater than 1, so there are $49-9=\boxed{40}$ odd square-free integers less than $100$.
